                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" id="antimony_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">a chemical element. <span class="dh">Antimony</span> is a silver-white metal that breaks easily, used especially in making <span class="ndv" xt="ndv" tofix="" href="alloy_topg_1">alloys</span>.</span></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="antimony_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late Middle English (denoting stibnite, the most common ore of the metal): from medieval Latin <span class="ei">antimonium</span>, of unknown origin. The current sense dates from the early 19th cent.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
